\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 System Development Life Cycle Baseline
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall manage Elko County information systems using a formally defined System Development Life Cycle (SDLC) that incorporates information security and privacy considerations at every phase,
 from initiation through disposal,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-3 (System Development Life Cycle).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall protect pre-production environments,
 including development,
 test,
 and integration environments,
 commensurate with risk throughout the system development life cycle,
 consistent with NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 SA-3(1) (Manage Preproduction Environment).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Acquisition Process and Contracting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall not initiate engagements involving third-party systems or External Service Providers absent Assessment Approval per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Supply Chain Risk Management (SCRM) and Vendor Governance) and Technical Approval per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.10"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (IT Financial Management and Procurement Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure third-party contracts obligate External Service Providers to execute secure development processes consistent with NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 SA-8 and CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure third-party contracts explicitly identify the functions,
 ports,
 protocols,
 and services employed,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-9(2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
For all system,
 system component,
 or system service acquisitions,
 the Assistant IT Director shall ensure the following requirements are included explicitly or by reference in the acquisition contract,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-4 (Acquisition Process):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(a) Security and privacy functional requirements;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(b) Strength of mechanism requirements;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(c) Security and privacy assurance requirements;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(d) Controls needed to satisfy the security and privacy requirements;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(e) Security and privacy documentation requirements;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(f) Requirements for protecting security and privacy documentation;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(g) Description of the system development environment and the environment in which the system is intended to operate;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(h) Allocation of accountability for information security,
 privacy,
 and supply chain risk management;
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
(i) Acceptance criteria.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Security and Privacy Engineering Principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall apply County-documented security and privacy engineering principles in the specification,
 design,
 development,
 implementation,
 and modification of all systems and system components,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall implement the privacy principle of minimization,
 using only the Personally Identifiable Information (PII) strictly necessary to perform system engineering and development tasks,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-8(33).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall not permit pre-production environments to contain Criminal Justice Information or Restricted data unless the environment is authorized and controlled to the same baseline required for production handling of that data classification per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Data Governance and Classification Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall not permit pre-production environments to contain unmasked Confidential data without IT Director authorization,
 consistent with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Developer Configuration Management,
 Testing,
 and Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Applicability
\series default
:
 The developer testing,
 evaluation,
 and assessment-plan requirements in this section shall apply to:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Software,
 scripts,
 or system components developed or acquired for execution on production systems;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Software,
 scripts,
 or system components that process,
 store,
 or transmit Criminal Justice Information,
 Restricted data,
 or Confidential data;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Software,
 scripts,
 or system components that perform authentication,
 authorization,
 access control,
 or audit logging functions;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All deliverables developed by External Service Providers;
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Software intended for shared use,
 scheduled execution,
 or deployment beyond the authoring individual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Ad-hoc administrative tooling executed interactively by authorized personnel against their own work product is not subject to this section.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Version Control and Configuration Integrity
\series default
:
 The Systems Administrator shall maintain version control over all internal development artifacts,
 including source code,
 scripts,
 and configuration files.
 Changes to development tools and processes shall be documented and managed to facilitate supply chain risk assessment,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-10 (Developer Configuration Management).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Developer Testing and Evaluation
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall require,
 for all software meeting the criteria in the Applicability bullet above,
 a documented security and privacy assessment plan executed during development.
 Required testing shall include,
 at minimum,
 functional testing,
 integration testing,
 regression testing,
 and information security testing,
 with rigor proportionate to the criticality of the software's function and the sensitivity of the data it handles,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-15(1) (Criticality Analysis).
 The assessment plan and test results shall be documented and provided to the Assistant IT Director as verifiable evidence of execution prior to system acceptance,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-11 (Developer Testing and Evaluation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Development Process Standards
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review development tools,
 standards,
 and methodologies no less frequently than annually to confirm they satisfy security and privacy requirements throughout the development life cycle,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-15 (Development Process,
 Standards,
 and Tools).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Flaw Remediation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall require all internal developers and External Service Providers to implement a verifiable flaw remediation process consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-11.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall remediate all flaws identified during development,
 testing,
 or post-deployment operation according to the severity-based schedule established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Vulnerability and Patch Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall not promote into production any system containing an unmitigated Critical or High severity flaw.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Production Promotion Gate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator shall promote SDLC outputs to production environments only following documented change authorization issued under the change authorization framework defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Change Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 End of Life and Unsupported System Components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Acquisition-time controls in this policy prohibit County entry into engagements that depend on unsupported system components.
 Operational governance of components that become unsupported during their service life is governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall not approve acquisition of any system or system component for which the developer,
 vendor,
 or manufacturer has ceased to provide analytical support,
 software updates,
 or security patches,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-22 (Unsupported System Components).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall not approve retention of an unsupported component beyond the vendor's declared end-of-support date except under a Risk Acceptance Memo issued per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct and document a market survey within the preceding ninety (90) calendar days prior to any request for retention authorization,
 confirming that no vendor-supported replacement product or approved support alternative is commercially available that meets the functional requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Intellectual Property and Source Code Ownership
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall enforce the following ownership terms to ensure the continuous security,
 maintainability,
 and auditability of Elko County systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall ensure that all software,
 source code,
 scripts,
 configurations,
 and related intellectual property engineered or developed by Elko County employees remains the exclusive and sole property of Elko County.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall ensure that all software and related intellectual property developed by External Service Providers,
 contractors,
 or vendors utilizing Elko County systems,
 funding,
 or data becomes the exclusive property of Elko County upon creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Any deviation from this ownership model —
 including commercial-off-the-shelf software licensing,
 shared-rights agreements,
 or vendor retention of underlying intellectual property —
 shall be documented in a legally binding contract and processed in accordance with the exception management framework defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and the Risk Acceptance Memo procedure defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IT Director shall not authorize commencement of development or deployment without documented exception approval.
\end_layout

